00:00:42.780 --> 00:00:45.800
I want to address a question,
which actually came up

00:00:45.800 --> 00:00:48.410
in discussions with
several of the students.

00:00:48.410 --> 00:00:54.340
And this is, I realize
that some people said, OK.

00:00:54.340 --> 00:00:55.890
Everything makes sense.

00:00:55.890 --> 00:00:57.510
But what are we plotting?

00:00:57.510 --> 00:00:59.600
What is really squeezed?

00:00:59.600 --> 00:01:02.170
Are we squeezing in
the spatial domain?

00:01:02.170 --> 00:01:04.780
Are we squeezing in
the temporal domain?

00:01:04.780 --> 00:01:07.840
So the plots look wonderful,
with these ellipses

00:01:07.840 --> 00:01:08.960
and the circles.

00:01:08.960 --> 00:01:11.870
But, what is it really
we are doing here?

00:01:11.870 --> 00:01:14.140
So let me address that.

00:01:14.140 --> 00:01:37.760
First of all, we are talking
about a single harmonic

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:39.100
oscillator.

00:01:39.100 --> 00:01:43.140
We showed that the
[INAUDIBLE] equations

00:01:43.140 --> 00:01:46.890
can be reduced to a bunch of
harmonic oscillator equations.

00:01:46.890 --> 00:01:49.630
One for each mode.

00:01:49.630 --> 00:01:52.400
And now we are
talking, today and

00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:56.400
in the previous few classes,
about one single mode,

00:01:56.400 --> 00:01:58.710
about one harmonic oscillator.

00:01:58.710 --> 00:02:02.760
And the harmonic oscillator
has canonically variables

00:02:02.760 --> 00:02:05.040
of momentum and position.

00:02:05.040 --> 00:02:08.479
But this is just to make
a connection for you

00:02:08.479 --> 00:02:10.919
with something you have learned.

00:02:10.919 --> 00:02:15.000
What we are talking about is
a single harmonic oscillator,

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:19.010
which is one single mode of
the electromagnetic field.

00:02:19.010 --> 00:02:21.650
So maybe let me draw
a cartoon for that.

00:02:24.880 --> 00:02:28.880
So let's assume
we have a cavity.

00:02:28.880 --> 00:02:32.950
We have an electromagnetic wave.

00:02:32.950 --> 00:02:36.700
There is propagation,
where it's e to the ikz.

00:02:36.700 --> 00:02:39.300
There is transverse confinement.

00:02:39.300 --> 00:02:41.580
Maybe there is a
Gaussian e to the minus

00:02:41.580 --> 00:02:47.350
x squared plus y squared over
sum [INAUDIBLE] parameter.

00:02:47.350 --> 00:02:53.430
All of that is simply
the spatial mode.

00:02:53.430 --> 00:02:55.980
And we just take that for
given because we're not

00:02:55.980 --> 00:02:58.260
solving the spatial
differential equation.

00:02:58.260 --> 00:03:03.400
All we are doing is we are
looking at this one mode.

00:03:03.400 --> 00:03:06.720
And the two degrees
of freedom is

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:11.230
that this mode can have a
certain number of photons.

00:03:11.230 --> 00:03:12.520
It's the amplitude.

00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:15.850
And the second one is you
can see the temporal phase.

00:03:15.850 --> 00:03:18.930
It can be a cosine omega t.
it can be a sine omega t.

00:03:18.930 --> 00:03:21.040
It can be a superposition.

00:03:21.040 --> 00:03:25.080
But whatever we are talking
about is in this mode.

00:03:25.080 --> 00:03:27.730
There is nothing happening
in the spatial domain.

00:03:27.730 --> 00:03:32.230
They're just asking, what is
the oscillation in this mode?

00:03:32.230 --> 00:03:34.070
The whole mode does
what it should.

00:03:34.070 --> 00:03:37.100
It has a prefect, of
which is the amplitude.

00:03:37.100 --> 00:03:40.440
And it has a temporal effect
of which we factor out.

00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:42.710
And this is what we
are talking about.

00:03:48.210 --> 00:03:51.500
Let me be a little
bit more specific

00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:59.780
and say, that when we
are plotting things,

00:03:59.780 --> 00:04:05.240
we are plotting the Q
representation, the phase space

00:04:05.240 --> 00:04:09.220
representation of the
statistical operator,

00:04:09.220 --> 00:04:12.640
which is simply describing
this single mode

00:04:12.640 --> 00:04:14.740
of the harmonic oscillator.

00:04:14.740 --> 00:04:17.870
And by performing the
diagram matrix elements,

00:04:17.870 --> 00:04:22.580
we obtain the Q distribution.

00:04:22.580 --> 00:04:26.320
In that case, we
have the vacuum.

00:04:26.320 --> 00:04:31.620
We have a displaced vacuum,
which is in coherent state.

00:04:31.620 --> 00:04:37.700
And our x's are, from
the very definition,

00:04:37.700 --> 00:04:39.990
in the complex plane
with a real part

00:04:39.990 --> 00:04:41.391
of the imaginary part of alpha.

00:04:47.340 --> 00:04:54.210
However, we can also
define [? the  Veetner ?]

00:04:54.210 --> 00:04:57.060
distribution, which is another
phase based distribution.

00:04:57.060 --> 00:04:59.930
It's almost the same
as the Q distribution.

00:04:59.930 --> 00:05:01.770
It's just this little
bit smeared out

00:05:01.770 --> 00:05:04.750
by h bar because of
some commutators.

00:05:04.750 --> 00:05:06.660
But nothing you
have to worry about.

00:05:06.660 --> 00:05:14.560
In that case, the
projection of the W function

00:05:14.560 --> 00:05:19.520
on the vertical
axis, on the y-axis,

00:05:19.520 --> 00:05:23.925
is the momentum wave
function squared.

00:05:29.735 --> 00:05:36.425
On the x-axis, it is the
spatial wave function

00:05:36.425 --> 00:05:38.020
squared of the
harmonic oscillator.

00:05:41.730 --> 00:05:44.590
So therefore, we
may sometimes think,

00:05:44.590 --> 00:05:48.440
when we have a distribution
here, we project it.

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:52.490
And we see what is the
momentum distribution.

00:05:52.490 --> 00:05:55.510
Or what is the
spatial distribution

00:05:55.510 --> 00:05:58.430
of the mechanical
harmonic oscillator.

00:05:58.430 --> 00:06:01.170
Which is analogous,
which is equivalent,

00:06:01.170 --> 00:06:05.340
to the one mode of the
electromagnetic field

00:06:05.340 --> 00:06:08.080
we are using.

00:06:08.080 --> 00:06:10.520
I know it may help
you to some extent

00:06:10.520 --> 00:06:17.470
to think about the P and Q.
But it may also be misleading

00:06:17.470 --> 00:06:20.540
because it gives you the
impression something is moving

00:06:20.540 --> 00:06:23.240
with a momentum
P, in real space.

00:06:23.240 --> 00:06:28.480
Let me therefore
emphasize what are

00:06:28.480 --> 00:06:34.640
the normalized forms of P and Q.

00:06:34.640 --> 00:06:40.750
If I do the symmetric and
anti-symmetric combination

00:06:40.750 --> 00:06:48.400
of the annihilation
and creation operator,

00:06:48.400 --> 00:06:51.730
I over squared root 2.

00:06:51.730 --> 00:06:56.230
I call those a1 and a2.

00:07:00.720 --> 00:07:11.740
And they are nothing
else than Q and P

00:07:11.740 --> 00:07:20.560
normalized by the characteristic
momentum of spatial coordinates

00:07:20.560 --> 00:07:23.560
of the harmonic oscillator.

00:07:23.560 --> 00:07:29.460
So what is important
here is that a1 and a2--

00:07:29.460 --> 00:07:30.840
forget about P,Q now.

00:07:30.840 --> 00:07:32.280
They are equivalent.

00:07:32.280 --> 00:07:35.250
But for the
electromagnetic field,

00:07:35.250 --> 00:07:41.670
a1 and a2 have a very
direct interpretation.

00:07:41.670 --> 00:07:47.180
They are called the two
quadrature operators.

00:07:47.180 --> 00:07:51.160
And what I mean by
that becomes clear

00:07:51.160 --> 00:07:55.430
when I use the
Heisenberg representation

00:07:55.430 --> 00:07:56.610
for the electric field.

00:08:00.390 --> 00:08:05.530
And I'm here using
the formula which

00:08:05.530 --> 00:08:12.780
is given in the book of
Weissbluth, in page 175.

00:08:12.780 --> 00:08:14.516
Some pages copied
from this book have

00:08:14.516 --> 00:08:17.160
been posted on the website.

00:08:17.160 --> 00:08:22.470
So we have our
normalization factor,

00:08:22.470 --> 00:08:30.950
which is related to the electric
field of a single photon.

00:08:30.950 --> 00:08:32.402
We have the polarization factor.

00:08:36.820 --> 00:08:42.309
But now we have an
expression which

00:08:42.309 --> 00:08:50.710
involves the quadrature
operators, a1 and a2.

00:08:56.810 --> 00:08:59.990
Just to be specific, we
are not in a cavity here.

00:08:59.990 --> 00:09:04.090
Therefore, we have propagating
waves cosine (kr) sine (kr).

00:09:04.090 --> 00:09:08.600
But you can also immediately
use a similar expression

00:09:08.600 --> 00:09:11.970
for the case of a cavity.

00:09:15.190 --> 00:09:19.040
Let us specify that r equals 0.

00:09:19.040 --> 00:09:24.670
And then we realize what the
two quadrature operators are.

00:09:24.670 --> 00:09:33.290
a2 is the operator which
creates and annihilates

00:09:33.290 --> 00:09:36.560
an electromagnetic
field, so to speak,

00:09:36.560 --> 00:09:42.670
photons, which have
an electric field.

00:09:42.670 --> 00:09:46.970
Which oscillates
as cosine omega t.

00:09:46.970 --> 00:09:52.756
And a1 is the quadrature
operator for the sine omega t

00:09:52.756 --> 00:09:53.255
component.

00:09:56.250 --> 00:10:00.590
So therefore, if you simply
analyze the electric field,

00:10:00.590 --> 00:10:05.830
what is cosine omega 2 is
related to the a2 quadrature

00:10:05.830 --> 00:10:06.740
operator.

00:10:06.740 --> 00:10:11.270
The sine omega 2 oscillation
is related to the a1 quadrature

00:10:11.270 --> 00:10:11.770
operator.

00:10:15.240 --> 00:10:18.850
So life would be
easier, but more boring,

00:10:18.850 --> 00:10:23.330
if you could create a
pure cosine, or pure sine

00:10:23.330 --> 00:10:25.640
oscillation of the
electromagnetic field.

00:10:25.640 --> 00:10:31.210
But you can't because a1
and a2 do not commute.

00:10:31.210 --> 00:10:33.730
And there is an
uncertainty relation

00:10:33.730 --> 00:10:39.750
that delta a1 times delta a2
is larger or equal to 1/2.

00:10:39.750 --> 00:10:45.189
And we have the equal sign
for coherent states alpha.

00:10:51.240 --> 00:10:57.250
So therefore, if we look
at the electric field,

00:10:57.250 --> 00:10:58.810
you know, everything
moves around

00:10:58.810 --> 00:11:02.390
periodically in r because
it's a traveling wave and t

00:11:02.390 --> 00:11:04.270
because it's an
oscillating wave.

00:11:04.270 --> 00:11:08.490
So let's not confuse things
with simply peak r equals 0.

00:11:08.490 --> 00:11:09.730
We've already done that.

00:11:09.730 --> 00:11:12.500
But now let's peak t equals 0.

00:11:12.500 --> 00:11:14.980
That t equals 0.

00:11:14.980 --> 00:11:17.370
The sine omega t is 0.

00:11:17.370 --> 00:11:24.360
And therefore, the distribution
for a2, the expectation value,

00:11:24.360 --> 00:11:29.330
and the variance for the
quadrature operator, a2,

00:11:29.330 --> 00:11:32.360
can be simply read off by
looking at the electric field.

00:11:36.340 --> 00:11:48.530
So, in other words,
at t equals 0,

00:11:48.530 --> 00:11:51.010
the electric field,
which is obtained

00:11:51.010 --> 00:11:56.800
by projecting our quasi
probabilities on the y-axis,

00:11:56.800 --> 00:12:02.110
gives the expectation
value for a1

00:12:02.110 --> 00:12:11.205
and the variant,
delta a1 squared.

00:12:16.580 --> 00:12:18.190
Somebody says 2.

00:12:18.190 --> 00:12:20.811
That t equals 0.

00:12:20.811 --> 00:12:21.310
Yes.

00:12:26.530 --> 00:12:27.030
Yes.

00:12:30.140 --> 00:12:33.740
And now, if you want to see what
the other quadrature component

00:12:33.740 --> 00:12:34.780
is, well.

00:12:34.780 --> 00:12:38.790
We just wait a quarter period
until the sine, which was 0,

00:12:38.790 --> 00:12:39.740
is maximum.

00:12:39.740 --> 00:12:42.650
And the cosine omega t is 0.

00:12:42.650 --> 00:12:53.360
So therefore, it's
pi over 2 omega,

00:12:53.360 --> 00:12:58.465
using the projection on
the y-axis, gives us a1.

00:13:01.060 --> 00:13:03.725
And delta a1 squared.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.780
Or, alternatively, we
don't need to wait.

00:13:16.780 --> 00:13:19.910
We can do t equals 0.

00:13:19.910 --> 00:13:21.685
And we can project
onto the x-axis.

00:13:43.570 --> 00:13:46.100
Let me just throw few
things into this diagram.

00:13:46.100 --> 00:13:48.750
If you had a classical
motion, which

00:13:48.750 --> 00:13:59.220
would simply be cosine omega t.

00:13:59.220 --> 00:14:11.280
Then that would mean, if
you had a motion which

00:14:11.280 --> 00:14:21.100
where only cosine
omega t-- yes, it

00:14:21.100 --> 00:14:24.590
would be a point on the y-axis.

00:14:24.590 --> 00:14:27.310
However, classically
we can never

00:14:27.310 --> 00:14:30.180
have something which
is just cosine omega t.

00:14:30.180 --> 00:14:33.800
The point has to
blurred into a circle.

00:14:33.800 --> 00:14:37.400
This is the coherent state.

00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:42.940
So this coherent state has
now-- let me just call it 1,

00:14:42.940 --> 00:14:44.870
for the sake of the
argument-- the point

00:14:44.870 --> 00:14:46.980
would be the
classical oscillator.

00:14:46.980 --> 00:14:48.810
It is just cosine omega t.

00:14:48.810 --> 00:14:50.390
Everything is deterministic.

00:14:50.390 --> 00:14:51.310
No uncertainty.

00:14:51.310 --> 00:14:54.110
No nothing.

00:14:54.110 --> 00:14:57.450
Of course, it means that
the time of evolution,

00:14:57.450 --> 00:14:58.920
it goes in a circle.

00:14:58.920 --> 00:15:02.170
But this is what everything
does in an harmonic oscillator

00:15:02.170 --> 00:15:07.540
when time evolves into the
e to the i omega t factor.

00:15:07.540 --> 00:15:09.260
So let's not get
confused with it.

00:15:09.260 --> 00:15:11.405
Let's just look at t equals 0.

00:15:14.080 --> 00:15:17.400
And we input [INAUDIBLE]
if r equals 0,

00:15:17.400 --> 00:15:20.790
the classical
oscillator is one point.

00:15:20.790 --> 00:15:23.520
But now, we have a spread here.

00:15:23.520 --> 00:15:26.790
This says that trying
to mechanically

00:15:26.790 --> 00:15:29.050
the amplitude of the
cosine omega t term

00:15:29.050 --> 00:15:31.236
is not entirely false.

00:15:31.236 --> 00:15:32.360
It's not [INAUDIBLE] sharp.

00:15:32.360 --> 00:15:34.010
There are fluctuations.

00:15:34.010 --> 00:15:38.760
And in addition, we have
ellipse in this direction,

00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:40.900
which we project
onto the x-axis.

00:15:40.900 --> 00:15:44.490
And this tells us what the
distribution in our ensemble,

00:15:44.490 --> 00:15:46.110
in our kind of
mechanical ensemble,

00:15:46.110 --> 00:15:49.500
is for the amplitudes of
the sine omega t motion.

00:15:52.580 --> 00:15:55.910
So the best we can do
is try to mechanically--

00:15:55.910 --> 00:16:00.350
if you want to have something,
which is really just cosine

00:16:00.350 --> 00:16:02.280
omega t.

00:16:02.280 --> 00:16:08.500
We have to squeeze it, that the
cosine omega t amplitude is now

00:16:08.500 --> 00:16:10.430
extremely sharp.

00:16:10.430 --> 00:16:14.410
But the sine omega t
amplitude in the ensemble

00:16:14.410 --> 00:16:17.360
is completely smeared out.

00:16:17.360 --> 00:16:18.960
So this is what
we're talking about.

00:16:24.360 --> 00:16:27.740
Now, what I think has
confused some of you

00:16:27.740 --> 00:16:30.990
is what I thought was
a wonderful example.

00:16:30.990 --> 00:16:33.310
The classical
squeezing experiment.

00:16:33.310 --> 00:16:36.340
I mean, these are visuals which
will be in your head forever,

00:16:36.340 --> 00:16:39.630
when you saw Professor
Pritchard with a circle pendulum

00:16:39.630 --> 00:16:40.790
he's just pulling.

00:16:40.790 --> 00:16:44.340
And then the circle
squeezes into an ellipse.

00:16:44.340 --> 00:16:48.820
And it seems that something
here is squeezed in real space.

00:16:48.820 --> 00:16:50.830
But this is actually wrong.

00:16:50.830 --> 00:16:53.040
But how you should have
looked at the experiment,

00:16:53.040 --> 00:16:55.590
and I made a comment
about it, but maybe not

00:16:55.590 --> 00:16:57.090
emphatically enough.

00:16:57.090 --> 00:17:00.830
You should have really thought
about a single pendulum.

00:17:00.830 --> 00:17:04.579
And this single pendulum, if
it has an [INAUDIBLE] phase,

00:17:04.579 --> 00:17:09.400
is in a superposition of sine
omega t and cosine omega t.

00:17:09.400 --> 00:17:13.599
And if you pull on the string,
if you shorten and lengthen

00:17:13.599 --> 00:17:17.180
the pendulum, it's
sine 2 omega t.

00:17:17.180 --> 00:17:22.079
You will amplify the prefactor
in front of sine omega t.

00:17:22.079 --> 00:17:25.020
And you will exponentially
de-amplify the factor

00:17:25.020 --> 00:17:27.440
in front of cosine omega t.

00:17:27.440 --> 00:17:31.420
So therefore, what will happen
if this pendulum oscillates--

00:17:31.420 --> 00:17:37.080
and let me say with a phase,
well, sine omega t plus delta,

00:17:37.080 --> 00:17:38.650
if delta is 90 degrees.

00:17:38.650 --> 00:17:39.940
Cosine if delta is 0.

00:17:39.940 --> 00:17:40.930
It's sine.

00:17:40.930 --> 00:17:45.580
And let's say this pendulum
oscillates at 45 degrees.

00:17:45.580 --> 00:17:49.100
Sine omega t plus 45 degrees.

00:17:49.100 --> 00:17:54.170
If you now parametrically
derive it with squeezing action,

00:17:54.170 --> 00:17:58.504
it would now mean
that you, let's

00:17:58.504 --> 00:17:59.795
just make it a sine convention.

00:17:59.795 --> 00:18:01.470
You de-amplify the cosine.

00:18:01.470 --> 00:18:02.850
You amplify the sine.

00:18:02.850 --> 00:18:06.320
And after a while, instead of
oscillating with sine omega

00:18:06.320 --> 00:18:09.130
t plus 45 degrees,
it will oscillate

00:18:09.130 --> 00:18:12.676
with an amplified
amplitude at sine omega t.

00:18:12.676 --> 00:18:13.800
This is what you have done.

00:18:16.790 --> 00:18:20.430
And this is a
mechanical analogy.

00:18:20.430 --> 00:18:26.070
There is, of course,
no squeezing in any way

00:18:26.070 --> 00:18:29.010
because in a
classical pendulum, we

00:18:29.010 --> 00:18:32.590
start with one definite value.

00:18:32.590 --> 00:18:34.250
If you prepare the system well.

00:18:34.250 --> 00:18:37.840
And then, we just
change the motion.

00:18:37.840 --> 00:18:38.910
We amplify.

00:18:38.910 --> 00:18:42.430
We pick out a phase and
that's what we are doing.

00:18:42.430 --> 00:18:46.580
Now the true ways how classical
squeezing can come in.

00:18:46.580 --> 00:18:53.320
One it is if the motion of
the pendulum is-- maybe there

00:18:53.320 --> 00:18:54.640
is an uncertainty.

00:18:54.640 --> 00:18:58.230
Maybe Professor Pritchard did
experiments with an ion trap.

00:18:58.230 --> 00:19:00.770
And actually, 20 years
