let me just also
get another question

00:35:55.660 --> 00:35:59.040
out of the system, which I've
been asked several times.

00:35:59.040 --> 00:36:02.010
People ask me,
well, the problem is

00:36:02.010 --> 00:36:05.890
that the ellipse
rotates like this.

00:36:05.890 --> 00:36:08.680
Isn't there a way--
now I need my hand--

00:36:08.680 --> 00:36:12.450
that we can have an
ellipse rotating like this?

00:36:12.450 --> 00:36:13.950
And that would be great.

00:36:13.950 --> 00:36:17.980
But this is sort of unnatural
because the harmonic oscillator

00:36:17.980 --> 00:36:18.970
does that.

00:36:18.970 --> 00:36:23.240
So if you wanted to do that,
you need an operator which

00:36:23.240 --> 00:36:26.990
is really, at every cycle of
the electromagnetic field,

00:36:26.990 --> 00:36:29.300
is when the light want
to sort of do this.

00:36:29.300 --> 00:36:30.080
No.

00:36:30.080 --> 00:36:31.380
Always push it back.

00:36:31.380 --> 00:36:32.810
And this is impractical.

00:36:32.810 --> 00:36:35.200
You need, really, an oscillator
which would completely

00:36:35.200 --> 00:36:39.080
change the quadrature components
of your harmonic oscillator

00:36:39.080 --> 00:36:42.730
in every single cycle of
the electromagnetic field.

00:36:42.730 --> 00:36:46.570
But sort of what homodyne
detection is, instead

00:36:46.570 --> 00:36:50.860
of now forcing the light to
stay aligned to sort of do

00:36:50.860 --> 00:36:53.050
this, which is
very unnatural, we

00:36:53.050 --> 00:36:55.700
allow the light
to freely evolve.

00:36:55.700 --> 00:36:59.560
But we have now an observer,
our local oscillator,

00:36:59.560 --> 00:37:04.180
which is rotating
synchronously with the ellipse.

00:37:04.180 --> 00:37:07.610
So we have a local oscillator
which is cosine omega t.

00:37:07.610 --> 00:37:10.920
It does, so to speak, exactly
what the ellipse is doing.

00:37:10.920 --> 00:37:13.070
So in that sense,
the local oscillator

00:37:13.070 --> 00:37:16.960
allows us, now, to
observe the ellipse always

00:37:16.960 --> 00:37:17.957
from its narrow side.

00:37:17.957 --> 00:37:20.040
Because the local oscillator
is [? cooperating ?].

00:37:22.504 --> 00:37:24.670
But the mathematics is
pretty much the [? Fourier ?]

00:37:24.670 --> 00:37:25.170
transform.

00:37:25.170 --> 00:37:30.262
The mathematics is a
[? Fourier ?] transform.

00:37:30.262 --> 00:37:32.470
The physics is the physics
of a [INAUDIBLE] detector.

00:37:38.780 --> 00:37:48.750
OK, now the only question
remaining is, how do we mix?

00:37:48.750 --> 00:37:53.850
How do we get a
product of our signal

00:37:53.850 --> 00:37:57.290
and the strong local oscillator?

00:37:57.290 --> 00:38:00.430
In an old radio, it's
done by an element.

00:38:00.430 --> 00:38:03.100
Maybe a diode, which
is a nonlinear circuit.

00:38:03.100 --> 00:38:06.360
If you drive a nonlinear
element with two input sources,

00:38:06.360 --> 00:38:10.290
you get something which
involves the product of the two.

00:38:15.630 --> 00:38:20.980
OK, so the principal
of homodyne detection

00:38:20.980 --> 00:38:28.120
is now that we want to mix
light at the beam splitter.

00:38:28.120 --> 00:38:32.080
So the device which
does all that for us

00:38:32.080 --> 00:38:38.720
is, after using so many
words, I would say it's

00:38:38.720 --> 00:38:40.320
disgustingly simple.

00:38:40.320 --> 00:38:44.070
It's really a half [INAUDIBLE].

00:38:44.070 --> 00:38:45.960
We talked about
beam splitters a lot

00:38:45.960 --> 00:38:48.780
here because beam
splitters perform

00:38:48.780 --> 00:38:51.340
wonderful unitary
transformations.

00:38:51.340 --> 00:38:55.480
And we'll exploit them
for many purposes.

00:38:55.480 --> 00:39:03.640
For the purpose of
this lecture, I simply

00:39:03.640 --> 00:39:08.540
assume that we have a
50-50 beam splitter.

00:39:08.540 --> 00:39:13.420
So, what I'm telling you
now about the beam splitter

00:39:13.420 --> 00:39:15.260
will be generalized.

00:39:15.260 --> 00:39:19.970
Either later today, or in
the lecture on Wednesday.

00:39:19.970 --> 00:39:26.100
So a beam splitter has two
input ports and output ports.

00:39:26.100 --> 00:39:29.790
We have light impinging
on the beam splitter.

00:39:29.790 --> 00:39:34.920
We call those modes a and b.

00:39:34.920 --> 00:39:46.070
And after the beam splitter,
we have two output modes.

00:39:46.070 --> 00:39:50.820
And let me call them a0 and b0.

00:39:50.820 --> 00:39:57.030
And what we measure is the
output of the beam splitter.

00:39:57.030 --> 00:39:58.840
So we have two photo detectors.

00:39:58.840 --> 00:40:00.080
And we measure the output.

00:40:12.700 --> 00:40:14.790
OK.

00:40:14.790 --> 00:40:22.070
The output modes, a
naught and b naught,

00:40:22.070 --> 00:40:33.070
are simply obtained by
taking the input modes

00:40:33.070 --> 00:40:35.020
and propagating them.

00:40:35.020 --> 00:40:37.480
We have two modes, a, b.

00:40:37.480 --> 00:40:41.160
You can say, what
goes vertically is a.

00:40:41.160 --> 00:40:42.055
Vertical is a.

00:40:42.055 --> 00:40:42.930
We call it a naught.

00:40:42.930 --> 00:40:43.710
Here, it's b.

00:40:43.710 --> 00:40:45.250
It becomes b naught.

00:40:45.250 --> 00:40:52.480
And what we have
to do is we have

00:40:52.480 --> 00:41:04.915
two transform the
operator a naught.

00:41:04.915 --> 00:41:06.040
Let me just make a comment.

00:41:08.332 --> 00:41:09.790
Sometimes in the
beam splitter, you

00:41:09.790 --> 00:41:14.210
want to think a quantum state
comes and is transformed.

00:41:14.210 --> 00:41:17.180
But instead of transforming
the state of a photon,

00:41:17.180 --> 00:41:19.450
I can also transform
the operator,

00:41:19.450 --> 00:41:20.705
which creates a photon.

00:41:20.705 --> 00:41:22.030
One is the Heisenberg picture.

00:41:22.030 --> 00:41:23.530
One is a Schrodinger picture.

00:41:23.530 --> 00:41:26.080
So right now, I'll use
the Heisenberg picture.

00:41:26.080 --> 00:41:28.160
I have two operators, a, b.

00:41:30.920 --> 00:41:34.500
Before the beam splitter is set,
I have two operators, a naught,

00:41:34.500 --> 00:41:35.200
b naught.

00:41:35.200 --> 00:41:38.870
Afterwards, I have
two other operators.

00:41:38.870 --> 00:41:40.040
I have operators a, b.

00:41:40.040 --> 00:41:42.520
Afterwards, i have operators
a naught, b naught.

00:41:42.520 --> 00:41:45.390
And, if you do the
time evolution,

00:41:45.390 --> 00:41:47.560
it's a unitary transformation.

00:41:47.560 --> 00:41:53.670
And for operators, we have
to multiply the operators

00:41:53.670 --> 00:41:55.560
from the left and
right hand side,

00:41:55.560 --> 00:42:00.350
with unitary operator,
u and u dagger.

00:42:00.350 --> 00:42:03.660
And we really talk
about the beam splitter

00:42:03.660 --> 00:42:06.720
in its full beauty
in a short while.

00:42:09.610 --> 00:42:11.930
It will be a special case
of what we discuss later.

00:42:11.930 --> 00:42:15.590
But I think it's pretty obvious
that a 50-50 beam splitters is

00:42:15.590 --> 00:42:18.420
simply creating two modes.

00:42:18.420 --> 00:42:21.040
One of the symmetric
combination.

00:42:21.040 --> 00:42:23.265
And one of the anti
symmetric combination.

00:42:29.620 --> 00:42:30.120
OK.

00:42:30.120 --> 00:42:36.900
So in our homodyne
detector, we are now

00:42:36.900 --> 00:42:42.965
measuring the number of
photons in the mode a naught.

00:42:45.550 --> 00:42:47.850
We measure with
the upper detector,

00:42:47.850 --> 00:42:50.560
the number of photons
in the mode b naught.

00:42:50.560 --> 00:42:53.980
But what we are then
doing is we run it

00:42:53.980 --> 00:42:56.810
through a different [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:56.810 --> 00:42:58.350
We want to cancel
certain noises,

00:42:58.350 --> 00:43:00.060
as you will see in a moment.

00:43:00.060 --> 00:43:07.000
This is why we
obtain the difference

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:09.800
signal, which we call I minus.

00:43:09.800 --> 00:43:13.420
So let's now calculate
what I minus is.

00:43:13.420 --> 00:43:20.110
Well, the number of photons
in the mode a naught

00:43:20.110 --> 00:43:21.825
is a naught dagger a naught.

00:43:21.825 --> 00:43:27.470
That's the operator for
the number of photons.

00:43:27.470 --> 00:43:32.180
We subtract b naught
dagger b naught.

00:43:32.180 --> 00:43:36.770
And, as you can
immediately see, is

00:43:36.770 --> 00:43:41.030
that it because of the
beam splitter, this

00:43:41.030 --> 00:43:46.280
is now involving a
product of a and b.

00:43:46.280 --> 00:43:49.800
ab dagger plus a dagger b.

00:43:49.800 --> 00:43:52.780
So in other words,
when you ask yourself,

00:43:52.780 --> 00:43:57.390
how can we-- remember, I said
we peak out the cosine omega t

00:43:57.390 --> 00:44:00.180
component by
multiplying our signal

00:44:00.180 --> 00:44:03.090
with the local oscillator.

00:44:03.090 --> 00:44:05.550
And you would say,
how do you multiply

00:44:05.550 --> 00:44:09.540
two modes of the
electromagnetic field?

00:44:09.540 --> 00:44:12.040
Well, just send it
to a beam splitter.

00:44:12.040 --> 00:44:15.190
In a beam splitter, you
create the sum of them.

00:44:15.190 --> 00:44:18.760
But then your photo detector
is square [INAUDIBLE] detector.

00:44:18.760 --> 00:44:21.290
You measure the electric
fields squared or you

00:44:21.290 --> 00:44:24.350
have to measure the
operator, a dagger a.

00:44:24.350 --> 00:44:28.380
And now, you get the [INAUDIBLE]
between ab dagger and a dagger

00:44:28.380 --> 00:44:31.250
b.

00:44:31.250 --> 00:44:34.320
So this is how we
multiply two operators.

00:44:34.320 --> 00:44:40.340
How we get a signal, which is
a proportional to a or a dagger

00:44:40.340 --> 00:44:41.857
times b or b dagger.

00:44:49.820 --> 00:44:52.790
By the way, if it wouldn't
take the difference,

00:44:52.790 --> 00:44:57.210
we get terms of aa
dagger bb dagger.

00:44:57.210 --> 00:44:59.730
Just the mode a or the
mode b by themselves.

00:44:59.730 --> 00:45:01.150
And we want to get rid of them.

00:45:01.150 --> 00:45:03.615
And by taking the difference
between the two photo

00:45:03.615 --> 00:45:07.290
detectors, those parts of
the signal are becoming mode.

00:45:07.290 --> 00:45:09.940
And are subtracted out.

00:45:09.940 --> 00:45:12.780
So therefore, this is
called balanced homodyne

00:45:12.780 --> 00:45:15.100
because we have the
balanced beam splitter.

00:45:15.100 --> 00:45:16.390
We measure to two signals.

00:45:16.390 --> 00:45:18.650
And then we take the
difference of the two signals.

00:45:24.380 --> 00:45:24.880
OK.

00:45:29.570 --> 00:45:31.590
There's one more
thing we have to add.

00:45:31.590 --> 00:45:37.050
And then we find we understand
the balanced homodyne

00:45:37.050 --> 00:45:37.640
detection.

00:45:37.640 --> 00:45:41.740
We want to explore it.

00:45:41.740 --> 00:45:44.590
That our mode b,
remember we want

00:45:44.590 --> 00:45:46.990
to measure mode a. a squeezed.

00:45:46.990 --> 00:45:50.460
a has quantum properties.
a has only single photons.

00:45:50.460 --> 00:45:56.360
And b is just a trick to
project out the cosine omega t.

00:45:56.360 --> 00:46:10.670
And we do that by choosing
for b a strong coherent state,

00:46:10.670 --> 00:46:13.430
described by a coherent
state parameter beta.

00:46:24.850 --> 00:46:27.790
Of course, whenever we have
a strong coherent state,

00:46:27.790 --> 00:46:32.850
that means that we
can replace b by beta,

00:46:32.850 --> 00:46:37.370
and b dagger by beta star.

00:46:37.370 --> 00:46:39.440
This is sort of
the classical field

00:46:39.440 --> 00:46:41.600
limit of a strong
coherent state.

00:46:45.010 --> 00:46:53.740
And now we can ask, what this
our different signal I minus?

00:46:53.740 --> 00:46:59.180
Well, the coherent state depends
on the phase angle theta.

00:46:59.180 --> 00:47:00.670
So it will be phase sensitive.

00:47:00.670 --> 00:47:04.170
It will depend on
the angle theta.

00:47:04.170 --> 00:47:05.730
But now there is one more thing.

00:47:05.730 --> 00:47:09.180
And that is, if you use a
stronger coherent state,

00:47:09.180 --> 00:47:14.680
of course both of our outputs
go up in proportion to beta.

00:47:14.680 --> 00:47:19.180
So therefore, we want
to go to a normalization

00:47:19.180 --> 00:47:22.200
by dividing by beta.

00:47:22.200 --> 00:47:24.270
So this is now our
normalized output.

00:47:39.740 --> 00:47:41.550
I'm looking at this.

00:47:41.550 --> 00:47:46.120
So this is our operator
for the signal I minus.

00:47:46.120 --> 00:47:48.270
And that is a.

00:47:48.270 --> 00:47:56.060
b has been replaced by, b dagger
has been replaced by b star.

00:47:56.060 --> 00:48:01.540
That gives us a times
e to the-- because

00:48:01.540 --> 00:48:04.050
of the complex
conjugation-- minus i

00:48:04.050 --> 00:48:11.870
theta plus a dagger times e
to the i theta divided by 2.

00:48:16.990 --> 00:48:25.540
So therefore, if we
choose the phase to be 0,

00:48:25.540 --> 00:48:28.200
we measure this
symmetric combination,

00:48:28.200 --> 00:48:30.020
a plus a dagger over 2.

00:48:40.140 --> 00:48:45.570
And this is-- just
comparing notes--

00:48:45.570 --> 00:48:49.440
simply the a1 quadrature
operator divided by square root

00:48:49.440 --> 00:48:51.190
2.

00:48:51.190 --> 00:48:57.250
And if you put a phase shifter,
just a dispersive element,

00:48:57.250 --> 00:48:59.270
into the strong local
oscillator and shift

00:48:59.270 --> 00:49:05.040
the phase by pi over 2, by
delaying the light pulse

00:49:05.040 --> 00:49:09.200
by a quarter wavelength, what
we are now projecting out

00:49:09.200 --> 00:49:15.810
is the other
quadrature component.

00:49:18.800 --> 00:49:22.250
So therefore, using
the beam splitter

00:49:22.250 --> 00:49:24.460
and the local
oscillator, we can now

00:49:24.460 --> 00:49:28.960
measure the expectation
value for a1 and for a2.

00:49:31.800 --> 00:49:34.990
I've posted a few papers
on the website which

00:49:34.990 --> 00:49:37.140
show some of the pioneering
experiments where

00:49:37.140 --> 00:49:39.440
people did exactly that.

00:49:39.440 --> 00:49:46.070
So then, when they observed the
quadrature comportment, which

00:49:46.070 --> 00:49:50.230
was squeezed, they usually
did it for a squeezed vacuum,

00:49:50.230 --> 00:49:53.540
so a1 and a2 had 0
expectation value.

00:49:53.540 --> 00:49:56.840
But the interesting part is,
how much noise was there?

00:49:56.840 --> 00:50:02.200
If you don't squeeze, you find
that your normalized noise

00:50:02.200 --> 00:50:05.860
simply corresponds to the
classical photon shot noise.

00:50:05.860 --> 00:50:08.820
But if you are
squeezed, you find

00:50:08.820 --> 00:50:10.895
that one quadrature
comportment has

00:50:10.895 --> 00:50:13.320
a smaller noise than shot noise.

00:50:13.320 --> 00:50:15.600
So [INAUDIBLE] photons
in your different signal.

00:50:15.600 --> 00:50:17.396
And your noise is less
than square root n.

00:50:17.396 --> 00:50:18.770
Where as in the
other quadrature,

00:50:18.770 --> 00:50:21.080
the component is larger.

00:50:21.080 --> 00:50:24.890
So you can look up
on the website papers

00:50:24.890 --> 00:50:29.220
where people slowly varied the
phase of the local oscillator.

00:50:29.220 --> 00:50:31.600
And you see, this
is shot noise, how

00:50:31.600 --> 00:50:33.155
the noise is below shot noise.

00:50:33.155 --> 00:50:34.410
Exceeds shot noise.

00:50:34.410 --> 00:50:35.540
It's below shot noise.

00:50:35.540 --> 00:50:37.200
And exceeds shot noise.

00:50:37.200 --> 00:50:41.110
And this was the first
evidence for the generation

00:50:41.110 --> 00:50:41.880
of squeezed light.

00:50:49.280 --> 00:50:49.780
Questions?

00:51:00.540 --> 00:51:01.040
OK.

00:51:01.040 --> 00:51:05.750
So we have discussed
the detection

00:51:05.750 --> 00:51:09.960
of squeezed light using
balanced homodyne detector.

00:51:09.960 --> 00:51:15.750
And balanced means that the
beam splitter was 50-50.

00:51:15.750 --> 00:51:19.720
So now we are ready to
discuss the unbalanced case.

00:51:30.250 --> 00:51:38.300
So let's get our
unbalanced beam splitter

00:51:38.300 --> 00:51:41.680
and, just for the
sake of the argument,

00:51:41.680 --> 00:51:46.840
let's say it has a really
good transmission of tt.

00:51:46.840 --> 00:51:49.930
So transmission
coefficient t squared

00:51:49.930 --> 00:51:53.090
tells you what fraction of
the power is transmitted.

00:51:53.090 --> 00:51:56.435
And let's just assume for
the sake of the argument, 99%

00:51:56.435 --> 00:51:58.370
are transmitted.

00:51:58.370 --> 00:52:01.480
So therefore, if we
start with our signal

00:52:01.480 --> 00:52:04.540
a, which may be
[INAUDIBLE] squeezed

00:52:04.540 --> 00:52:06.130
quantum state, number state.

00:52:06.130 --> 00:52:09.020
You name it.

00:52:09.020 --> 00:52:12.245
a naught is pretty
much the same as a.

00:52:12.245 --> 00:52:15.180
We haven't lost so much.

00:52:15.180 --> 00:52:20.170
But now we use our
local oscillator,

00:52:20.170 --> 00:52:21.105
which is very strong.

00:52:24.740 --> 00:52:29.680
Only a very small fraction
of it will be reflected.

00:52:29.680 --> 00:52:32.540
But we can always compensate
for the small reflection

00:52:32.540 --> 00:52:36.370
by making b even stronger.

00:52:36.370 --> 00:52:38.490
Let's see what we get.

00:52:38.490 --> 00:52:42.630
So the mode, a naught,
the output mode,

00:52:42.630 --> 00:52:46.550
is now the transmission
coefficient times a.

00:52:49.480 --> 00:52:50.530
a and a.

00:52:50.530 --> 00:52:53.070
The operators are amplitudes.

00:52:53.070 --> 00:52:56.730
So we have to use, if you
have a 99% beam splitter,

00:52:56.730 --> 00:52:59.990
we have to take the
square root of 0.99.

00:52:59.990 --> 00:53:02.540
This is the transmission
coefficient.

00:53:02.540 --> 00:53:05.480
And now we have the
transmission coefficient

00:53:05.480 --> 00:53:08.920
for the strong local
oscillator, which

00:53:08.920 --> 00:53:12.800
we will again approximate
by its eigenvalue.

00:53:12.800 --> 00:53:13.950
Coherent state eigenvalue.

00:53:18.320 --> 00:53:21.150
And the reflection coefficient
is 1 minus t squared.

00:53:25.820 --> 00:53:33.156
So if we make the approximation
that t is approximately 1,

00:53:33.156 --> 00:53:34.780
we can take it out
off the parenthesis.

00:53:44.780 --> 00:53:45.980
And we obtain that.

00:53:48.750 --> 00:53:53.690
If t is close to 1,
we can neglect it.

00:53:53.690 --> 00:53:58.300
And what we see now is
what we have obtained

00:53:58.300 --> 00:54:03.210
is actually the original
quantum state a.

00:54:03.210 --> 00:54:03.910
Or I should say.

00:54:03.910 --> 00:54:04.720
The operator.

00:54:04.720 --> 00:54:06.030
I'm in the Heisenberg picture.

00:54:06.030 --> 00:54:11.320
a is the mode
operator for the input

00:54:11.320 --> 00:54:14.740
of the unbalanced
homodyne detector.

00:54:14.740 --> 00:54:19.460
And what we have simply done is
we have displaced the operator.

00:54:19.460 --> 00:54:22.620
We have displaced
the mode operator a.

00:54:22.620 --> 00:54:26.920
And the displacement operator
has an [? argument ?]

00:54:26.920 --> 00:54:33.670
of 1 minus t squared beta.

00:54:33.670 --> 00:54:36.360
And this is a
Hermitian conjugate.

00:54:36.360 --> 00:54:41.880
1 minus t squared beta.

00:54:41.880 --> 00:54:45.820
So what I've shown you here
is that the local oscillator

00:54:45.820 --> 00:54:52.740
and the beam splitter is the
realization, or implementation,

00:54:52.740 --> 00:54:54.140
of the displacement operator.

00:55:02.440 --> 00:55:08.090
So in the limit that
t goes to unity,

00:55:08.090 --> 00:55:12.000
we are not losing anything
of out quantum state.

00:55:12.000 --> 00:55:15.680
But by reflecting
in the amplitude

00:55:15.680 --> 00:55:20.520
of a strong coherent state, we
simply take our quantum state,

00:55:20.520 --> 00:55:24.810
and we displace it in this
two dimensional plane.

00:55:24.810 --> 00:55:28.500
So that's what this beam
splitter does for us.

00:55:35.557 --> 00:55:36.140
Any questions?

00:55:44.440 --> 00:55:46.420
In the next few
classes, we really

00:55:46.420 --> 00:55:48.360
